00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:12.120 align:middle line:90%
>> Welcome to "Into the Vortex."

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:13.620 align:middle line:84%
I'm your host Jimmy
Church, and this

00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:16.860 align:middle line:84%
is an exciting time for all of
humanity with the James Webb

00:01:16.860 --> 00:01:18.120 align:middle line:90%
Space Telescope.

00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:20.682 align:middle line:84%
Josh, today we have
John Michael Godier.

00:01:20.682 --> 00:01:21.640 align:middle line:90%
Are you ready for this?

00:01:21.640 --> 00:01:23.640 align:middle line:84%
>> I'm excited the implications
about the telescope are

00:01:23.640 --> 00:01:25.840 align:middle line:84%
profound, and I'm excited
to hear more from you.

00:01:25.840 --> 00:01:26.640 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:01:26.640 --> 00:01:27.990 align:middle line:90%
>> Absolutely extraordinary.

00:01:27.990 --> 00:01:30.090 align:middle line:90%
And welcome, John.

00:01:30.090 --> 00:01:33.280 align:middle line:90%
But we got to go straight here.

00:01:33.280 --> 00:01:36.690 align:middle line:84%
What is the James
Webb Space Telescope?

00:01:36.690 --> 00:01:40.950 align:middle line:10%
>> A long time in coming because
it has taken several decades

00:01:40.950 --> 00:01:44.250 align:middle line:10%
to get this telescope to become
a reality after initially

00:01:44.250 --> 00:01:45.280 align:middle line:10%
planning and funding it.

00:01:45.280 --> 00:01:48.100 align:middle line:84%
But it had cost overruns and
took a very, very long time

00:01:48.100 --> 00:01:48.900 align:middle line:90%
to get right.

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:51.210 align:middle line:10%
However, once it
was launched, which

00:01:51.210 --> 00:01:54.953 align:middle line:10%
was a picture perfect
launch, it was truly perfect.

00:01:54.953 --> 00:01:56.370 align:middle line:10%
Nothing went wrong
with the launch

00:01:56.370 --> 00:01:57.495 align:middle line:10%
and the deployment of Webb.

00:01:57.495 --> 00:02:00.510 align:middle line:10%
It had over 250
possible failure points,

00:02:00.510 --> 00:02:02.430 align:middle line:10%
and not a single
thing went wrong.

00:02:02.430 --> 00:02:04.680 align:middle line:10%
The telescope deployed
and positioned itself

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:06.810 align:middle line:10%
at L2, which is a
gravitational point that's

00:02:06.810 --> 00:02:08.940 align:middle line:10%
advantageous for a
telescope like this,

00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:12.460 align:middle line:10%
and began test photography
a few months ago.

00:02:12.460 --> 00:02:15.090 align:middle line:10%
Now, we are at the point where
actual science is being done,

00:02:15.090 --> 00:02:17.340 align:middle line:10%
and we're getting the first
images from the telescope.

00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:18.840 align:middle line:84%
And they're
spectacular, beating out

00:02:18.840 --> 00:02:20.590 align:middle line:90%
anything we've ever had before.

00:02:20.590 --> 00:02:27.150 align:middle line:84%
>> Now, the stated mission is to
look for extraterrestrial life

00:02:27.150 --> 00:02:29.160 align:middle line:84%
out there, not only
in our Milky Way,

00:02:29.160 --> 00:02:30.780 align:middle line:90%
but throughout the universe.

00:02:30.780 --> 00:02:33.930 align:middle line:84%
In your view, what do you
think the stated mission is?

00:02:33.930 --> 00:02:36.570 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, the stated
mission for James W.

00:02:36.570 --> 00:02:39.930 align:middle line:84%
Webb Space Telescope is
effectively to study many

00:02:39.930 --> 00:02:43.780 align:middle line:84%
different astronomical phenomena
using the infrared spectrum.

00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:45.690 align:middle line:10%
So it will do a
variety of science,

00:02:45.690 --> 00:02:47.940 align:middle line:10%
but including in that is
looking for exoplanets.

00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:49.980 align:middle line:10%
Because this
telescope is uniquely

00:02:49.980 --> 00:02:53.610 align:middle line:10%
suited for being able
to try to characterize

00:02:53.610 --> 00:02:56.760 align:middle line:10%
the atmospheres of
exoplanets-- distant ones.

00:02:56.760 --> 00:02:58.140 align:middle line:10%
And if you can do
that-- and it's

00:02:58.140 --> 00:03:01.740 align:middle line:10%
done by these planets passing
in front of their star

00:03:01.740 --> 00:03:04.260 align:middle line:10%
blocking a little bit
of light and coloring

00:03:04.260 --> 00:03:06.190 align:middle line:10%
that light with
their atmosphere,

00:03:06.190 --> 00:03:07.710 align:middle line:10%
which allows the
scientists to look

00:03:07.710 --> 00:03:10.980 align:middle line:10%
at the spectroscopy of
this exoplanet's atmosphere

00:03:10.980 --> 00:03:12.630 align:middle line:10%
and see what it's made up of.

00:03:12.630 --> 00:03:16.062 align:middle line:10%
Well, if you start seeing weird
levels of oxygen and methane,

00:03:16.062 --> 00:03:17.520 align:middle line:10%
things that shouldn't
be there-- we

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:20.850 align:middle line:10%
call them disequilibriums, where
the oxygen should be present.

00:03:20.850 --> 00:03:22.980 align:middle line:10%
It should react with
everything and rust everything

00:03:22.980 --> 00:03:24.910 align:middle line:10%
and do all of these
sorts of things.

00:03:24.910 --> 00:03:26.670 align:middle line:84%
But if something is
replenishing that,

00:03:26.670 --> 00:03:30.090 align:middle line:84%
as what happens here on Earth,
what's doing that here on Earth

00:03:30.090 --> 00:03:31.360 align:middle line:90%
is plant life.

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:33.180 align:middle line:84%
So that would be
a good indicator

00:03:33.180 --> 00:03:37.740 align:middle line:84%
that there is some type of
biosphere on that exoplanet

00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:40.030 align:middle line:84%
if you start seeing
those weird levels.

00:03:40.030 --> 00:03:42.990 align:middle line:10%
The other things that you may
see are things like CFCs--

00:03:42.990 --> 00:03:45.060 align:middle line:10%
artificial chemicals
in an atmosphere

00:03:45.060 --> 00:03:48.060 align:middle line:10%
that might tell you
that possibly there

00:03:48.060 --> 00:03:50.490 align:middle line:10%
is an extraterrestrial
civilization burning

00:03:50.490 --> 00:03:52.800 align:middle line:10%
a hole in their ozone
layer with that.

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:54.485 align:middle line:90%
That was freon, essentially.

00:03:54.485 --> 00:03:55.860 align:middle line:10%
And those are the
types of things

00:03:55.860 --> 00:03:57.570 align:middle line:10%
that James Webb
can start to look

00:03:57.570 --> 00:04:00.390 align:middle line:10%
for to try to get
some idea if there

00:04:00.390 --> 00:04:02.070 align:middle line:10%
is a technosignature there.

00:04:02.070 --> 00:04:04.470 align:middle line:10%
But fundamentally, it
will try to characterize

00:04:04.470 --> 00:04:06.280 align:middle line:10%
all types of
exoplanet atmosphere

00:04:06.280 --> 00:04:07.890 align:middle line:10%
so that we got a
sampling of what

00:04:07.890 --> 00:04:10.860 align:middle line:10%
atmospheres are possible on
exoplanets in the universe.

00:04:10.860 --> 00:04:12.390 align:middle line:10%
And that will be
one thing it does.

00:04:12.390 --> 00:04:14.280 align:middle line:10%
But it will also
fundamentally look

00:04:14.280 --> 00:04:16.800 align:middle line:10%
at the very furthest
reaches of the universe

00:04:16.800 --> 00:04:20.250 align:middle line:10%
that it can at the very
beginning, just after the Big

00:04:20.250 --> 00:04:22.380 align:middle line:10%
Bang, and look at
the earliest galaxies

00:04:22.380 --> 00:04:25.230 align:middle line:10%
and how they formed, and
even the earliest stars.

00:04:25.230 --> 00:04:27.990 align:middle line:10%
There are stars
that we hypothesize

00:04:27.990 --> 00:04:30.990 align:middle line:10%
exist called Population III
stars that are very, very

00:04:30.990 --> 00:04:33.660 align:middle line:10%
early, have only mostly
hydrogen and helium in them,

00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:35.820 align:middle line:10%
were amongst the first
stars in the universe.

00:04:35.820 --> 00:04:38.160 align:middle line:10%
And through
gravitational lensing,

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:40.170 align:middle line:10%
we can actually see
examples of these.

00:04:40.170 --> 00:04:42.570 align:middle line:10%
One of them is known as
Earendel, which is a candidate,

00:04:42.570 --> 00:04:46.560 align:middle line:10%
and see what the very
earliest universe looked like,

00:04:46.560 --> 00:04:48.660 align:middle line:10%
as far as galaxies and stars go.

00:04:48.660 --> 00:04:50.740 align:middle line:90%
>> Let's jump back for a second.

00:04:50.740 --> 00:04:52.260 align:middle line:90%
You mentioned biosphere.

00:04:52.260 --> 00:04:53.970 align:middle line:90%
What is a biosphere?

00:04:53.970 --> 00:04:54.870 align:middle line:90%
>> You live in one.

00:04:54.870 --> 00:04:57.180 align:middle line:84%
Essentially, it is
an atmosphere that

00:04:57.180 --> 00:05:00.360 align:middle line:84%
is conducive for
life, a biogenesis,

00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:02.760 align:middle line:90%
to arise in and then adapt.

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:04.620 align:middle line:84%
Because what life
on Earth did was

00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:06.960 align:middle line:84%
it started with Earth's
original atmosphere

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:08.530 align:middle line:90%
and then oxygenated it.

00:05:08.530 --> 00:05:11.250 align:middle line:84%
So once we had the very
simple anaerobic life

00:05:11.250 --> 00:05:14.310 align:middle line:84%
arise on this planet, it
started producing oxygen

00:05:14.310 --> 00:05:16.080 align:middle line:90%
once it hit photosynthesis.

00:05:16.080 --> 00:05:18.300 align:middle line:84%
And that oxygenated
our atmosphere,

00:05:18.300 --> 00:05:21.510 align:middle line:84%
giving a very reactive
element for more complex life

00:05:21.510 --> 00:05:22.470 align:middle line:90%
to evolve.

00:05:22.470 --> 00:05:26.550 align:middle line:84%
And that's how we ended up
here is through that very, very

00:05:26.550 --> 00:05:30.060 align:middle line:84%
long-- billions of years
long process of Earth

00:05:30.060 --> 00:05:32.250 align:middle line:84%
changing its own
biosphere in order

00:05:32.250 --> 00:05:34.950 align:middle line:90%
to be more habitable for life.

00:05:34.950 --> 00:05:37.590 align:middle line:10%
Unfortunately, that didn't
benefit the very earliest life

00:05:37.590 --> 00:05:40.620 align:middle line:10%
on Earth, which oxygen
is poisonous to them.

00:05:40.620 --> 00:05:42.870 align:middle line:84%
So they now live
deep below the Earth

00:05:42.870 --> 00:05:45.270 align:middle line:84%
where there is no
oxygen and they--

00:05:45.270 --> 00:05:49.360 align:middle line:84%
>> So we're looking
essentially for other Earths?

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:50.160 align:middle line:90%
>> Absolutely.

00:05:50.160 --> 00:05:50.960 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:05:50.960 --> 00:05:55.740 align:middle line:84%
>> And a technosignature,
which we hear this a lot today,

00:05:55.740 --> 00:06:00.300 align:middle line:84%
and the imagination just
goes with what that may be.

00:06:00.300 --> 00:06:03.870 align:middle line:84%
What is a technosignature
and why would we look for it?

00:06:03.870 --> 00:06:07.140 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, a biosignature
is the sign of life.

00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:09.960 align:middle line:84%
You're looking for
algae and plants

00:06:09.960 --> 00:06:12.757 align:middle line:84%
because those would be the
most obvious signatures.

00:06:12.757 --> 00:06:14.340 align:middle line:10%
With a technosignature,
you're looking

00:06:14.340 --> 00:06:16.440 align:middle line:10%
for the mark of a civilization.

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:18.630 align:middle line:10%
You're looking for
the mark of technology

00:06:18.630 --> 00:06:20.730 align:middle line:10%
on the signal you see
with the telescope.

00:06:20.730 --> 00:06:22.440 align:middle line:10%
And there are many
ways this can happen.

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:24.880 align:middle line:10%
Radio astronomers look
for radio signals.

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:28.260 align:middle line:10%
And here, we're looking for
visual cues at exoplanets

00:06:28.260 --> 00:06:32.430 align:middle line:10%
with JWST to try to determine
if there is a technosignature

00:06:32.430 --> 00:06:34.200 align:middle line:10%
that we can tease out of that.

00:06:34.200 --> 00:06:37.788 align:middle line:10%
And, of course, that
remains to be seen.

00:06:37.788 --> 00:06:39.330 align:middle line:10%
But if you see
something weird, there

00:06:39.330 --> 00:06:41.640 align:middle line:10%
are things that
it could pick up.

00:06:41.640 --> 00:06:50.310 align:middle line:10%
>> Today, we understand now that
every star that we can see from

00:06:50.310 --> 00:06:53.760 align:middle line:10%
our backyard has at
least one planet.

00:06:53.760 --> 00:06:58.770 align:middle line:84%
This is an assumption now that
was fantasy just 20 years ago.

00:06:58.770 --> 00:07:02.700 align:middle line:84%
We still were wondering if
there were other planets

00:07:02.700 --> 00:07:04.090 align:middle line:90%
beyond our solar system.

00:07:04.090 --> 00:07:08.460 align:middle line:84%
Now, we know that every star
has a planet next to it.

00:07:08.460 --> 00:07:12.900 align:middle line:84%
The James Webb Space Telescope,
their deep field image--

00:07:12.900 --> 00:07:14.800 align:middle line:84%
Josh, can you pull
up the deep field?

00:07:14.800 --> 00:07:15.600 align:middle line:90%
>> Certainly.

00:07:15.600 --> 00:07:18.060 align:middle line:10%
>> When we look at the
deep field as opposed

00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:23.940 align:middle line:10%
to Hubble's original deep field
image, and we look at this.

00:07:23.940 --> 00:07:28.590 align:middle line:10%
First, we see a collection of
galaxies that goes on nearly

00:07:28.590 --> 00:07:29.850 align:middle line:10%
to infinity.

00:07:29.850 --> 00:07:34.930 align:middle line:10%
And each one of those
galaxies has 50 billion

00:07:34.930 --> 00:07:37.090 align:middle line:10%
to a trillion stars in it.

00:07:37.090 --> 00:07:40.750 align:middle line:10%
And each one of those
stars has a planet.

00:07:40.750 --> 00:07:45.100 align:middle line:10%
So we are potentially
looking at in this image

00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:49.300 align:middle line:10%
hundreds of trillions, trillions
of trillions of planets.

00:07:49.300 --> 00:07:52.210 align:middle line:10%
And it goes on
nearly to infinity.

00:07:52.210 --> 00:07:55.200 align:middle line:84%
>> It is possible that planets
actually outnumber stars

00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:56.000 align:middle line:90%
in the universe.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:56.980 align:middle line:90%
We don't know yet.

00:07:56.980 --> 00:08:00.550 align:middle line:10%
But it is possible that if--
each one of those stars--

00:08:00.550 --> 00:08:03.520 align:middle line:10%
each one of those galaxies
of 100 billion suns or more

00:08:03.520 --> 00:08:06.190 align:middle line:10%
may have more than
just one planet.

00:08:06.190 --> 00:08:08.950 align:middle line:10%
They may have eight
planets like ours does.

00:08:08.950 --> 00:08:11.470 align:middle line:10%
If enough of those
happen, then planets

00:08:11.470 --> 00:08:15.550 align:middle line:10%
outnumber even stars and the
observable universe, which is

00:08:15.550 --> 00:08:17.320 align:middle line:10%
a staggering amount of planets.

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:19.720 align:middle line:10%
There is no possible
way that this

00:08:19.720 --> 00:08:22.180 align:middle line:10%
could be the only one like
this that's inhabited.

00:08:22.180 --> 00:08:25.540 align:middle line:10%
>> Are you of the same mind--
you've been writing about

00:08:25.540 --> 00:08:29.350 align:middle line:10%
science and reporting on it
not only in our community,

00:08:29.350 --> 00:08:33.820 align:middle line:10%
but through other media
outlets for many years.

00:08:33.820 --> 00:08:39.039 align:middle line:84%
Are you now on board with
where science is today,

00:08:39.039 --> 00:08:43.549 align:middle line:84%
that there is not only life
out there, but infinite life,

00:08:43.549 --> 00:08:47.410 align:middle line:84%
and we have no idea how much
life is actually out there?

00:08:47.410 --> 00:08:50.140 align:middle line:84%
>> I would take the position
that I'm skeptical that we

00:08:50.140 --> 00:08:51.460 align:middle line:90%
would be alone.

00:08:51.460 --> 00:08:52.780 align:middle line:90%
How could that be?

00:08:52.780 --> 00:08:54.190 align:middle line:90%
I mean, how could that be?

00:08:54.190 --> 00:08:56.080 align:middle line:84%
If we were alone
in the universe,

00:08:56.080 --> 00:08:57.850 align:middle line:84%
just generally
speaking, this would

00:08:57.850 --> 00:09:01.870 align:middle line:84%
be like the island from Lost,
where chemical processes happen

00:09:01.870 --> 00:09:03.505 align:middle line:90%
here and nowhere else.

00:09:03.505 --> 00:09:05.380 align:middle line:84%
And I don't think that
gets mentioned enough,

00:09:05.380 --> 00:09:08.690 align:middle line:84%
that when you say that
we are probably alone,

00:09:08.690 --> 00:09:09.760 align:middle line:90%
that's a tall order.

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:13.560 align:middle line:84%
Because why should
we be special?

00:09:13.560 --> 00:09:15.770 align:middle line:84%
Why should this
planet be magical?

00:09:15.770 --> 00:09:17.060 align:middle line:90%
It'd be a unicorn.

00:09:17.060 --> 00:09:21.180 align:middle line:84%
So it's completely reasonable
to say there's probably

00:09:21.180 --> 00:09:21.980 align:middle line:90%
life out there.

00:09:21.980 --> 00:09:23.720 align:middle line:84%
There's probably a lot of
life, and there's probably

00:09:23.720 --> 00:09:24.500 align:middle line:90%
intelligent life.

00:09:24.500 --> 00:09:25.550 align:middle line:90%
It would not surprise me.

00:09:25.550 --> 00:09:27.170 align:middle line:90%
That's why I look for it.

00:09:27.170 --> 00:09:31.220 align:middle line:10%
>> Is the James Webb Space
Telescope the pinnacle--

00:09:31.220 --> 00:09:35.000 align:middle line:10%
the highest point of our
technology to this point?

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:39.740 align:middle line:10%
Is this the most extreme thing
that we have developed yet?

00:09:39.740 --> 00:09:42.270 align:middle line:10%
>> It's our best, most
capable instrument to date,

00:09:42.270 --> 00:09:44.600 align:middle line:10%
but it will eventually
be superseded.

00:09:44.600 --> 00:09:45.690 align:middle line:90%
There's bigger we can do.

00:09:45.690 --> 00:09:46.940 align:middle line:90%
We can do all sorts of things.

00:09:46.940 --> 00:09:50.900 align:middle line:84%
If you really want to search for
extraterrestrial intelligence,

00:09:50.900 --> 00:09:53.990 align:middle line:84%
