your comments here.

00:12:45.500 --> 00:12:48.710 align:middle line:10%
This is an extraordinary image.

00:12:48.710 --> 00:12:53.780 align:middle line:10%
And my question has always been,
how did we look at this before,

00:12:53.780 --> 00:12:56.210 align:middle line:10%
and what do we see, and
what's the difference here?

00:12:56.210 --> 00:12:58.140 align:middle line:10%
And what is actually going on?

00:12:58.140 --> 00:12:59.930 align:middle line:10%
This is a pretty amazing image.

00:12:59.930 --> 00:13:02.570 align:middle line:10%
>> That is a group of galaxies
interacting and colliding

00:13:02.570 --> 00:13:04.310 align:middle line:10%
galaxies called
Stephan's Quintet.

00:13:04.310 --> 00:13:07.010 align:middle line:10%
And what you're seeing
there is one of the galaxies

00:13:07.010 --> 00:13:07.820 align:middle line:10%
is not involved.

00:13:07.820 --> 00:13:09.080 align:middle line:10%
It's a foreground object.

00:13:09.080 --> 00:13:12.930 align:middle line:10%
But the other three you can see
are intermixing and interacting

00:13:12.930 --> 00:13:13.730 align:middle line:10%
with each other--

00:13:13.730 --> 00:13:14.780 align:middle line:10%
trading stars.

00:13:14.780 --> 00:13:16.700 align:middle line:10%
There are planets
and stars being

00:13:16.700 --> 00:13:19.850 align:middle line:10%
traded between those
galaxies gravitationally.

00:13:19.850 --> 00:13:22.070 align:middle line:10%
And what you're seeing is
that a sort of collision.

00:13:22.070 --> 00:13:24.140 align:middle line:10%
It's very slow, coalescing.

00:13:24.140 --> 00:13:27.380 align:middle line:10%
Now, what's different between
images we've seen of this--

00:13:27.380 --> 00:13:29.210 align:middle line:10%
and this particular
group of objects

00:13:29.210 --> 00:13:30.830 align:middle line:10%
was discovered in
the 19th century.

00:13:30.830 --> 00:13:32.990 align:middle line:10%
We've known about it
for a very long time.

00:13:32.990 --> 00:13:35.580 align:middle line:10%
What we're seeing is,
number one, in infrared,

00:13:35.580 --> 00:13:37.700 align:middle line:10%
which gives you details
that you normally

00:13:37.700 --> 00:13:40.820 align:middle line:10%
wouldn't see because visible
light can be blocked by dust.

00:13:40.820 --> 00:13:44.150 align:middle line:10%
Infrared makes it through
much more efficiently,

00:13:44.150 --> 00:13:46.630 align:middle line:10%
and you can actually see
through these dust clouds

00:13:46.630 --> 00:13:47.630 align:middle line:10%
and see what's in there.

00:13:47.630 --> 00:13:50.120 align:middle line:10%
So you get a much,
much greater ability

00:13:50.120 --> 00:13:51.410 align:middle line:10%
to see stuff going on there.

00:13:51.410 --> 00:13:53.330 align:middle line:10%
And it's at much
higher resolution

00:13:53.330 --> 00:13:55.310 align:middle line:10%
than we've ever
photographed before.

00:13:55.310 --> 00:14:01.180 align:middle line:10%
>> This next image
IC 5332, Josh.

00:14:01.180 --> 00:14:02.950 align:middle line:10%
>> It's an extraordinary image.

00:14:02.950 --> 00:14:05.990 align:middle line:10%
