Goldilocks zone, and we've

00:19:19.770 --> 00:19:21.870 align:middle line:90%
got too much to study now.

00:19:21.870 --> 00:19:23.400 align:middle line:90%
That's where we are.

00:19:23.400 --> 00:19:28.720 align:middle line:84%
But ET must be going through
the exact same thing.

00:19:28.720 --> 00:19:31.950 align:middle line:84%
They have their own version of
the James Webb Space Telescope.

00:19:31.950 --> 00:19:34.200 align:middle line:84%
They're looking out
into the universe

00:19:34.200 --> 00:19:35.670 align:middle line:90%
and across the Milky Way.

00:19:35.670 --> 00:19:38.610 align:middle line:90%
And they see our Earth.

00:19:38.610 --> 00:19:40.260 align:middle line:90%
They see our planet.

00:19:40.260 --> 00:19:43.800 align:middle line:84%
Depending on how far
away they are from us,

00:19:43.800 --> 00:19:46.620 align:middle line:84%
they could see us
nearly in real time.

00:19:46.620 --> 00:19:50.290 align:middle line:84%
They could see nearly you and I
having this conversation right

00:19:50.290 --> 00:19:51.090 align:middle line:90%
now.

00:19:51.090 --> 00:19:55.110 align:middle line:84%
Or they could look at the
distant past and dinosaurs

00:19:55.110 --> 00:19:58.740 align:middle line:84%
and extreme methane
going on in this planet.

00:19:58.740 --> 00:20:00.490 align:middle line:84%
But they would be
doing the same thing.

00:20:00.490 --> 00:20:04.210 align:middle line:84%
They are looking out
for planets with life.

00:20:04.210 --> 00:20:05.010 align:middle line:90%
>> They are.

00:20:05.010 --> 00:20:08.340 align:middle line:84%
And before I dig into that,
one odd thing about this

00:20:08.340 --> 00:20:10.920 align:middle line:84%
is that because a
telescope can only

00:20:10.920 --> 00:20:14.040 align:middle line:84%
work a certain way, like an
infrared telescope like James

00:20:14.040 --> 00:20:17.080 align:middle line:84%
Webb, it can only
operate a certain way.

00:20:17.080 --> 00:20:19.200 align:middle line:84%
So if you have an alien
civilization with science,

00:20:19.200 --> 00:20:21.307 align:middle line:84%
their telescope, at
least superficially,

00:20:21.307 --> 00:20:22.890 align:middle line:84%
is going to look a
lot like James Webb

00:20:22.890 --> 00:20:25.090 align:middle line:84%
because they're using the
same physical principles.

00:20:25.090 --> 00:20:26.910 align:middle line:84%
So if you ever want
to see what maybe

00:20:26.910 --> 00:20:29.760 align:middle line:84%
a piece of alien
technology might look like,

00:20:29.760 --> 00:20:32.088 align:middle line:84%
a radio telescope or
an optical telescope

00:20:32.088 --> 00:20:33.630 align:middle line:84%
is a good candidate
because they work

00:20:33.630 --> 00:20:36.900 align:middle line:84%
on rules that are common
to the entire universe.

00:20:36.900 --> 00:20:41.130 align:middle line:84%
Now, what they would see is
that every civilization doing

00:20:41.130 --> 00:20:43.530 align:middle line:84%
science with a large enough
telescope in the Milky Way

00:20:43.530 --> 00:20:47.700 align:middle line:84%
galaxy knows this planet
has a biosphere because it's

00:20:47.700 --> 00:20:52.170 align:middle line:84%
been screaming an oxygen methane
biosphere, a very unnatural one

00:20:52.170 --> 00:20:55.650 align:middle line:84%
outside of the context of
nature itself instead of life,

00:20:55.650 --> 00:20:56.940 align:middle line:90%
for billions of years.

00:20:56.940 --> 00:20:58.860 align:middle line:84%
The entire galaxy
has seen this planet,

00:20:58.860 --> 00:21:02.160 align:middle line:84%
and is aware that it's
here and hosts a biosphere.

00:21:02.160 --> 00:21:04.950 align:middle line:84%
What they can't see is
us because we've only

00:21:04.950 --> 00:21:07.380 align:middle line:84%
been producing technosignatures
for about 100 years--

00:21:07.380 --> 00:21:08.310 align:middle line:90%
a little longer.

00:21:08.310 --> 00:21:11.130 align:middle line:84%
And the radio waves
and indications of that

00:21:11.130 --> 00:21:13.170 align:middle line:84%
haven't propagated
out far enough.

00:21:13.170 --> 00:21:15.870 align:middle line:84%
They're only out
about 100 light years.

00:21:15.870 --> 00:21:18.442 align:middle line:84%
And so most of the
galaxy has not--

00:21:18.442 --> 00:21:19.650 align:middle line:90%
doesn't know that we're here.

00:21:19.650 --> 00:21:22.410 align:middle line:84%
They just would know that
there's a biosphere here.

00:21:22.410 --> 00:21:28.090 align:middle line:84%
>> Now, If that's the
case and they visit,

00:21:28.090 --> 00:21:31.780 align:middle line:84%
would we know what
we are looking at?

00:21:31.780 --> 00:21:36.490 align:middle line:84%
Would we understand that we
were looking at a species?

00:21:36.490 --> 00:21:41.500 align:middle line:84%
And certainly, it would
indicate thousands of species,

00:21:41.500 --> 00:21:45.970 align:middle line:84%
not just one, if they
all know that we're here.

00:21:45.970 --> 00:21:48.385 align:middle line:84%
Would we know what
we are looking at?

00:21:48.385 --> 00:21:51.010 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, that's a good question
because we only have a sampling

00:21:51.010 --> 00:21:51.810 align:middle line:90%
of one.

00:21:51.810 --> 00:21:52.920 align:middle line:90%
We know what we look like.

00:21:52.920 --> 00:21:53.720 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:21:53.720 --> 00:21:54.520 align:middle line:90%
Put it this way.

00:21:54.520 --> 00:21:56.890 align:middle line:84%
If it doesn't look like
anything you're familiar with,

00:21:56.890 --> 00:21:58.240 align:middle line:90%
you're never going to see it.

00:21:58.240 --> 00:21:59.080 align:middle line:90%
You'll just miss it.

00:21:59.080 --> 00:21:59.935 align:middle line:90%
You know, it's--

00:21:59.935 --> 00:22:00.220 align:middle line:90%
>> Why?

00:22:00.220 --> 00:22:02.890 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, because you don't have
any indicators on what to look

00:22:02.890 --> 00:22:03.690 align:middle line:90%
for.

00:22:03.690 --> 00:22:05.920 align:middle line:84%
We can think of a Dyson
sphere, so we look for that.

00:22:05.920 --> 00:22:09.140 align:middle line:84%
We can think of radio waves,
so we can look for that.

00:22:09.140 --> 00:22:11.680 align:middle line:84%
But what about things like a
nanotechnological cloud where

00:22:11.680 --> 00:22:14.930 align:middle line:84%
this civilization has uploaded
itself into this nanotechnology

00:22:14.930 --> 00:22:15.730 align:middle line:90%
cloud?

00:22:15.730 --> 00:22:17.938 align:middle line:84%
We have absolutely no idea
what that would look like.

00:22:17.938 --> 00:22:19.810 align:middle line:84%
We're just-- haven't
thought that far ahead,

00:22:19.810 --> 00:22:22.090 align:middle line:84%
so we don't know
what to look for.

00:22:22.090 --> 00:22:23.830 align:middle line:90%
So it just depends.

00:22:23.830 --> 00:22:26.920 align:middle line:84%
Because as Arthur Clarke
once said long ago,

00:22:26.920 --> 00:22:29.080 align:middle line:84%
"Any sufficiently
advanced technology

00:22:29.080 --> 00:22:30.543 align:middle line:90%
will appear as magic."

00:22:30.543 --> 00:22:31.960 align:middle line:84%
Well, there is
some wisdom to that

00:22:31.960 --> 00:22:34.180 align:middle line:84%
because we don't know
what they can do.

00:22:34.180 --> 00:22:36.940 align:middle line:84%
What's a-- what would our
civilization's technology

00:22:36.940 --> 00:22:38.500 align:middle line:90%
look like in a million years?

00:22:38.500 --> 00:22:41.030 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you can't really
extrapolate out that far.

00:22:41.030 --> 00:22:43.210 align:middle line:84%
So it may be that
we're invisible,

00:22:43.210 --> 00:22:47.500 align:middle line:84%
and that we live in a cloud
uploaded to a supercomputer.

00:22:47.500 --> 00:22:49.810 align:middle line:84%
And you'd never see that
anywhere outside of Earth.

00:22:49.810 --> 00:22:51.520 align:middle line:90%
So you just don't know.

00:22:51.520 --> 00:22:54.340 align:middle line:84%
But what you can do is
take shots in the dark

00:22:54.340 --> 00:22:57.010 align:middle line:84%
based on what you can
predict that they might do.

00:22:57.010 --> 00:22:59.530 align:middle line:90%
And that's all you've got.

00:22:59.530 --> 00:23:06.590 align:middle line:84%
>> Would we see them coming in
that faster than light travel--

00:23:06.590 --> 00:23:11.270 align:middle line:84%
well, then we wouldn't see them
coming until they were here.

00:23:11.270 --> 00:23:14.570 align:middle line:84%
If they're folding space, or
if there's a wormhole involved,

00:23:14.570 --> 00:23:18.320 align:middle line:84%
if they're ejecting out of
the back side of a black hole,

00:23:18.320 --> 00:23:20.690 align:middle line:84%
we wouldn't see
them arrive either.

00:23:20.690 --> 00:23:23.000 align:middle line:84%
So that's a weird
technosignature

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:26.750 align:middle line:84%
to look for when we wouldn't
see it to begin with

00:23:26.750 --> 00:23:28.820 align:middle line:84%
and wouldn't understand
it if we could.

00:23:28.820 --> 00:23:31.830 align:middle line:84%
So we wouldn't see
them until we got here,

00:23:31.830 --> 00:23:33.085 align:middle line:90%
which would explain a lot.

00:23:33.085 --> 00:23:34.460 align:middle line:84%
>> And it would
probably kill us.

00:23:34.460 --> 00:23:38.540 align:middle line:84%
Because if you have something
coming out of warp, so

00:23:38.540 --> 00:23:41.180 align:middle line:84%
to speak, and it's something
like an Alcubierre warp drive,

00:23:41.180 --> 00:23:43.472 align:middle line:84%
the amount of radiation that
thing is going to kick off

00:23:43.472 --> 00:23:46.010 align:middle line:84%
would irradiate half the planet
and cause a mass extinction.

00:23:46.010 --> 00:23:47.850 align:middle line:84%
That does not appear
to have happened.

00:23:47.850 --> 00:23:51.348 align:middle line:84%
So it just doesn't look
like it occurs unless they

00:23:51.348 --> 00:23:52.640 align:middle line:90%
have some way of mitigating it.

00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:53.940 align:middle line:90%
But how do you know?

00:23:53.940 --> 00:23:55.580 align:middle line:90%
I mean, what would they do?

00:23:55.580 --> 00:23:56.580 align:middle line:90%
What would they use?

00:23:56.580 --> 00:23:58.025 align:middle line:84%
So you just--
there's just no way

00:23:58.025 --> 00:24:01.790 align:middle line:84%
to-- you don't have any physical
indicators that you know about

00:24:01.790 --> 00:24:03.110 align:middle line:90%
to look for.

00:24:03.110 --> 00:24:05.360 align:middle line:84%
So without that
information about knowing

00:24:05.360 --> 00:24:08.480 align:middle line:84%
what to look for first, you
can't really make a detection.

00:24:08.480 --> 00:24:09.710 align:middle line:90%
So it's all just guesswork.

00:24:09.710 --> 00:24:12.650 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, maybe you can come
up with some ideas in maybe

00:24:12.650 --> 00:24:14.490 align:middle line:90%
how you could detect it.

00:24:14.490 --> 00:24:17.180 align:middle line:84%
But fundamentally,
it probably would

00:24:17.180 --> 00:24:18.860 align:middle line:90%
be something you don't expect.

00:24:18.860 --> 00:24:21.208 align:middle line:84%
And I imagine that they
probably don't want you to--

00:24:21.208 --> 00:24:23.750 align:middle line:84%
they probably don't want you to
know that they're there, so--

00:24:23.750 --> 00:24:28.610 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, part of your research
has focused on the theory

00:24:28.610 --> 00:24:31.910 align:middle line:84%
and the suggestion of
Von Neumann probes,

00:24:31.910 --> 00:24:37.310 align:middle line:84%
and that would be a way to
go out and not only map,

00:24:37.310 --> 00:24:42.530 align:middle line:84%
but check out other exoplanets
and move across the Milky Way

00:24:42.530 --> 00:24:46.100 align:middle line:84%
very quickly with a
self-replicating system

00:24:46.100 --> 00:24:47.420 align:middle line:90%
in place.

00:24:47.420 --> 00:24:51.950 align:middle line:84%
With what is happening today
through our own military

00:24:51.950 --> 00:24:54.740 align:middle line:84%
and observations of things
that we can't explain--

00:24:54.740 --> 00:24:59.510 align:middle line:84%
the various UAPs, the Tic
Tac videos, the eyewitness

00:24:59.510 --> 00:25:01.610 align:middle line:90%
testimony from pilots--

00:25:01.610 --> 00:25:03.470 align:middle line:90%
suggests just that.

00:25:03.470 --> 00:25:07.880 align:middle line:84%
And Von Neumann, in the late
'40s, came up with this theory,

00:25:07.880 --> 00:25:10.070 align:middle line:84%
and it seems that we are
living through it today.

00:25:10.070 --> 00:25:11.630 align:middle line:84%
Do you think that's
a possibility

00:25:11.630 --> 00:25:17.270 align:middle line:84%
that these civilizations
could have now arrived

00:25:17.270 --> 00:25:19.920 align:middle line:90%
through self-replicating probes?

00:25:19.920 --> 00:25:20.720 align:middle line:90%
>> Absolutely.

00:25:20.720 --> 00:25:23.510 align:middle line:84%
The Fermi paradox is
predicated on the notion

00:25:23.510 --> 00:25:25.460 align:middle line:84%
that if you have
enough time, it's

00:25:25.460 --> 00:25:27.810 align:middle line:84%
not hard to put a Von Neumann
probe in every star system

00:25:27.810 --> 00:25:28.610 align:middle line:90%
in the galaxy.

00:25:28.610 --> 00:25:32.660 align:middle line:84%
And the Milky Way is well
old enough, billions of years

00:25:32.660 --> 00:25:34.340 align:middle line:90%
old enough, to have done it.

00:25:34.340 --> 00:25:35.360 align:middle line:90%
So where are they?

00:25:35.360 --> 00:25:39.020 align:middle line:84%
You would expect to see some
evidence of them everywhere.

00:25:39.020 --> 00:25:40.500 align:middle line:90%
We don't.

00:25:40.500 --> 00:25:44.310 align:middle line:84%
So the one way, in order
to defeat the challenges

00:25:44.310 --> 00:25:46.290 align:middle line:84%
of crossing vast
amounts of space time,

00:25:46.290 --> 00:25:48.300 align:middle line:84%
is to do it with a
robot that doesn't care

00:25:48.300 --> 00:25:49.830 align:middle line:90%
about the passage of time--

00:25:49.830 --> 00:25:51.100 align:middle line:90%
your Von Neumann probe.

00:25:51.100 --> 00:25:53.070 align:middle line:84%
So it can go and
spend 100,000 years

00:25:53.070 --> 00:25:54.790 align:middle line:90%
crossing space to get somewhere.

00:25:54.790 --> 00:25:55.590 align:middle line:90%
It's a machine.

00:25:55.590 --> 00:25:58.310 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't care, as long
as it's still working.

00:25:58.310 --> 00:25:59.310 align:middle line:90%
It just shows up.

00:25:59.310 --> 00:26:02.220 align:middle line:84%
Doesn't-- passage of time
doesn't mean anything to it.

00:26:02.220 --> 00:26:04.780 align:middle line:90%
There, it could print out--

00:26:04.780 --> 00:26:06.510 align:middle line:90%
3D print out anything it wants.

00:26:06.510 --> 00:26:11.010 align:middle line:84%
And if it 3D printed
out an atmospheric probe

00:26:11.010 --> 00:26:13.830 align:middle line:84%
and entered the Earth's
atmosphere, which

00:26:13.830 --> 00:26:15.960 align:middle line:84%
is the most interesting
exoplanet in the system

00:26:15.960 --> 00:26:18.360 align:middle line:84%
and someone saw
it, there's a UAP.

00:26:18.360 --> 00:26:20.790 align:middle line:84%
So there is a plausible--
completely plausible way

00:26:20.790 --> 00:26:23.820 align:middle line:84%
through the Von Neumann
probe to play around

00:26:23.820 --> 00:26:27.690 align:middle line:84%
with the idea of the UAP, as the
various groups like the Galileo

00:26:27.690 --> 00:26:29.100 align:middle line:90%
Project study them.

00:26:29.100 --> 00:26:33.060 align:middle line:84%
>> Now, what about
communication?

00:26:33.060 --> 00:26:36.210 align:middle line:84%
Is that something
that we could expect

00:26:36.210 --> 00:26:39.330 align:middle line:84%
to see with a technosignature--
how communication

00:26:39.330 --> 00:26:41.520 align:middle line:84%
is happening, whether
it's through light

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:43.860 align:middle line:90%
or some other means?

00:26:43.860 --> 00:26:47.310 align:middle line:84%
But wouldn't these probes,
whatever they may be,

00:26:47.310 --> 00:26:52.260 align:middle line:84%
wouldn't they need to
communicate to a master

00:26:52.260 --> 00:26:55.920 align:middle line:84%
situation and then back to
the home planet too as well?

00:26:55.920 --> 00:26:57.965 align:middle line:90%
>> If the home planet matters.

00:26:57.965 --> 00:26:59.340 align:middle line:84%
If the Von Neumann
probe is like,

00:26:59.340 --> 00:27:00.930 align:middle line:90%
I don't care where I'm from.

00:27:00.930 --> 00:27:02.340 align:middle line:90%
I'm just here to do a job.

00:27:02.340 --> 00:27:05.670 align:middle line:84%
And whatever that job is, you'd
need to know its motivations,

00:27:05.670 --> 00:27:06.570 align:middle line:90%
and you can't.

00:27:06.570 --> 00:27:07.830 align:middle line:90%
I mean, how do we know?

00:27:07.830 --> 00:27:10.950 align:middle line:84%
If it's motivation is to simply
sit here and watch and make

00:27:10.950 --> 00:27:13.080 align:middle line:84%
sure that we never develop
artificial intelligence

00:27:13.080 --> 00:27:15.990 align:middle line:84%
or nanotechnology, we won't
know anything about it

00:27:15.990 --> 00:27:16.870 align:middle line:90%
until we do it.

00:27:16.870 --> 00:27:18.412 align:middle line:84%
And then all of a
sudden it stops us,

00:27:18.412 --> 00:27:21.000 align:middle line:84%
and that was its
purpose and done.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:24.570 align:middle line:84%
So highly speculative
as that is,

00:27:24.570 --> 00:27:27.700 align:middle line:84%
you just can't know the
motives of such a thing.

00:27:27.700 --> 00:27:29.640 align:middle line:84%
So it may not
communicate back home.

00:27:29.640 --> 00:27:32.410 align:middle line:84%
Or it may communicate--
again, Clarke tech.

00:27:32.410 --> 00:27:34.470 align:middle line:84%
You never know how
it could communicate.

00:27:34.470 --> 00:27:37.080 align:middle line:84%
Or it's really directional and
never points its radio signal

00:27:37.080 --> 00:27:37.740 align:middle line:90%
towards us.

00:27:37.740 --> 00:27:38.540 align:middle line:90%
>> Sure.

00:27:38.540 --> 00:27:46.150 align:middle line:84%
And there is also the mention
of certain frequencies.

00:27:46.150 --> 00:27:48.270 align:middle line:84%
And this is from the
Department of Defense.

00:27:48.270 --> 00:27:53.130 align:middle line:84%
This is also something that
came up in the UFO hearing

00:27:53.130 --> 00:27:55.620 align:middle line:84%
with the subcommittee
specifically talking

00:27:55.620 --> 00:28:00.210 align:middle line:84%
about these frequencies, and
were we able to lock on to this

00:28:00.210 --> 00:28:03.900 align:middle line:84%
and understand what was going
on and what the motivations were

00:28:03.900 --> 00:28:06.750 align:middle line:84%
with these different craft
that have been spotted.

00:28:06.750 --> 00:28:10.890 align:middle line:84%
Would we be able to lock
on to the home planet

00:28:10.890 --> 00:28:12.180 align:middle line:90%
through these frequencies?

00:28:12.180 --> 00:28:18.060 align:middle line:84%
And also, a GPS situation
here on our planet where

00:28:18.060 --> 00:28:20.370 align:middle line:90%
they may be going to?

00:28:20.370 --> 00:28:22.590 align:middle line:90%
Why focus on frequencies?

00:28:22.590 --> 00:28:26.640 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, that's a
two-tiered answer.

00:28:26.640 --> 00:28:30.750 align:middle line:84%
Because, as you know, radio
has an enormous number

00:28:30.750 --> 00:28:33.840 align:middle line:84%
of frequencies--
just a huge dial--

00:28:33.840 --> 00:28:37.090 align:middle line:84%
and a signal could be
placed at any of those.

00:28:37.090 --> 00:28:40.050 align:middle line:84%
So how do you know where to
look on the dial for the radio

00:28:40.050 --> 00:28:41.130 align:middle line:90%
signal?

00:28:41.130 --> 00:28:44.270 align:middle line:84%
There, with the UAP--
that's that frequency.

00:28:44.270 --> 00:28:45.070 align:middle line:90%
I've heard of it.

00:28:45.070 --> 00:28:47.290 align:middle line:84%
I don't know, but it
seems testable to me--

00:28:47.290 --> 00:28:50.460 align:middle line:84%
somebody tune to that
frequency and start listening

00:28:50.460 --> 00:28:51.780 align:middle line:90%
and see what you get.

00:28:51.780 --> 00:28:54.150 align:middle line:84%
As far as the rest
of it, what do

00:28:54.150 --> 00:28:57.660 align:middle line:84%
radio astronomers look for are
natural signals where it would

00:28:57.660 --> 00:29:00.510 align:middle line:84%
